definition.value: A benzene-derived hexacarboxylic acid in which each carbon of benzene carries a carboxy substituent.
An amphetamine that is propylbenzene substituted by a hydroxy group at position 1 and by an amino group at position 2 (the 1S,2S-stereoisomer).
A member of the class of  hydroquinones that is benzene-1,4-diol substituted by tert-butyl groups at position 2 and 5.
An amino sugar that is alpha-D-glucose in which the 2 and 6-hydroxy groups are replaced by amino groups.
An N-acetylmannosamine having pyranose form and alpha-D-configuration.
An beta-D-glucoside in which the anomeric hydrogen of beta-D-glucopyranose is substituted by an octyl group.
A but-2-enoic acid with a trans- double bond at C-2. It has been isolated from Daucus carota.
A member of the class of benzamides obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of 4-phenoxybenzoic acid with the amino group of (pyridin-2-yl)methylamine.
A quaternary ammonium ion in which the substituents on nitrogen are methyl (three) and carboxymethyl.
A pyrroline consisting of 2-pyrroline having methyl and carboxy substituents at positions 4 and 5 respectively.
A pyrimidine ribonucleoside 5'-monophosphate that is the 6-oxo derivative of UMP.
A ketotetrose phosphate that is D-erythrulose carrying a phosphono substituent at position O-4.
A sugar dianhydride obtained by the condensation of two units of beta-D-fructofuranose.
A biopterin in which the 1,2-dihydroxypropyl group has (1S,2R)-configuration.

A butanediol that is butane in which one hydrogen of each of the methyl groups is substituted by a hydroxy group. A colourless, water-miscible, viscous liquid at room temperature (m.p. 16degreeC) with a high boiling point (230degreeC), it is mainly used for the production of other organic chemicals, particularly the solvent oxolane (also known as tetrahydrofuran or THF).
